% ==============================================================================
% ABSTRACT
% ==============================================================================
\begin{abstract}
Graph of Convex Sets~(GCS) planning formulates motion planning as continuous
optimization over a graph of convex free-space regions, yet its performance
fundamentally depends on the quality and efficiency of region generation.
Existing approaches---IRIS and C-IRIS---either lack collision-safety
certificates or incur prohibitive computational costs, and all require full
reconstruction when obstacles change.
We present \emph{SafeBoxForest}~(SBF), a persistent C-space hyperrectangle
decomposition framework for GCS planning.
The core abstraction is a \emph{link-AABB envelope}: for each C-space box, SBF
computes bounding AABBs for every robot link in the workspace, then checks
these against obstacle AABBs to certify or reject the box---without
point-wise collision sampling.
We provide two complementary strategies that span a safety--tightness
tradeoff: \emph{interval forward kinematics}~(IFK) yields certified
conservative envelopes at $O(DL)$ cost;
\emph{critical-point sampling} produces tighter envelopes at higher cost
but without formal certification.
Orthogonal subdivision techniques bridge this gap, significantly tightening
IFK envelopes while preserving certification at sub-linear overhead.
SBF constructs a non-overlapping box forest via hierarchical cell
decomposition with BFS wavefront expansion, and its obstacle-independent
kinematic cache~(HCACHE) enables cross-scene reuse and incremental updates.
Experiments on a KUKA IIWA14 7-DOF manipulator show that SBF generates
certifiable regions substantially faster than C-IRIS, achieves
competitive free-space coverage, and reduces region update cost relative to
full IRIS reconstruction.
\end{abstract}

% ==============================================================================
% I. INTRODUCTION
% ==============================================================================
\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}

Graph of Convex Sets~(GCS)~\cite{marcucci2024motion}
formulates motion planning as continuous optimization over a graph whose
nodes are convex free-space regions, yielding high-quality trajectories
via convex relaxation of the underlying combinatorial structure.
However, planning quality depends critically on the
upstream \emph{region generation} step: how quickly and reliably can we
produce certified collision-free convex regions that cover the relevant
portion of configuration space~($\Cspace$)?
In industrial settings---assembly lines, human--robot
collaboration---obstacles change frequently while the same robot is queried
repeatedly, demanding efficient re-planning.
Current convex-region generators start from scratch each time, unable to
amortize computation across queries or scenes.

Existing approaches exhibit significant limitations.
IRIS~\cite{deits2015computing} iterates between workspace ellipsoids and
separating hyperplanes but does not directly produce C-space regions.
IRIS-NP~\cite{petersen2023growing} grows C-space polytopes via nonlinear
programming, achieving high volume but \emph{without providing a formal
collision-safety certificate}.
C-IRIS~\cite{werner2024certified} provides sum-of-squares~(SOS)
certification, yet a single region requires \emph{minutes} of computation,
preventing scalable deployment.
All three share two critical deficiencies:
(i)~no \emph{persistence}---any obstacle change necessitates full
reconstruction; and
(ii)~no cross-query reuse mechanism.

\textbf{Core observation.}
For a serial manipulator, given a C-space hyperrectangle
$B = \prod_{i=1}^{D}[\underline{q}_i,\overline{q}_i]$,
one can compute, for each link~$\ell$, a workspace axis-aligned bounding
box~(AABB) that encloses the link geometry for \emph{all}
$\bm{q} \in B$---a \emph{link-AABB envelope}
(\cref{fig:overview}).
The mapping ``C-space box $\to$ link-AABB vector'' serves as a unified
computation and caching unit that depends \emph{only} on robot kinematics,
\emph{not} on obstacles.
Under this framework, \emph{interval forward kinematics}~(IFK) provides
certified conservative envelopes at $O(D \cdot L)$ cost, while
\emph{critical-point sampling} produces tighter but non-certified envelopes.
Because envelopes are obstacle-independent, they naturally support
\emph{persistent caching} and cross-scene reuse: when obstacles change,
only collision checks must be redone, not the kinematics computation.

\textbf{Contributions.}
\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Link-AABB envelope framework and safety--tightness tradeoff}
  (\cref{sec:certification}):
  We propose a unified ``C-space box $\to$ workspace link-AABB vector''
  framework with two complementary strategies---IFK ($O(DL)$, certified,
  conservative) and critical-point sampling (tight, non-certified)---that
  quantify the safety--tightness tradeoff.
  Link subdivision and C-space box subdivision serve as general-purpose
  orthogonal enhancements applicable to either strategy, achieving
  significant tightness improvement at sub-linear time overhead.

\item \textbf{SafeBoxForest construction algorithm}
  (\cref{sec:sbf_construction,sec:sbf_forest}):
  Hierarchical C-space cell decomposition with BFS wavefront expansion and
  island bridging generates a non-overlapping certified box graph that
  directly inputs to GCS.

\item \textbf{Persistence and incremental updates}
  (\cref{sec:hcache,sec:incremental}):
  An obstacle-independent kinematic cache~(HCACHE) transforms region
  generation from ``rebuild every time'' to ``incremental maintenance,''
  with near-zero cross-scene loading overhead.

\item \textbf{Systematic experimental validation}
  (\cref{sec:experiments}):
  On a 7-DOF KUKA IIWA14 manipulator, we compare against C-IRIS
  and evaluate end-to-end planning performance, certified region
  generation efficiency, and incremental update behavior under obstacle
  changes.
\end{enumerate}

