  separation.
  \textbf{Right}: the resulting box forest~(colored) covers the free
  C-space; gray denotes obstacles.}
\label{fig:overview}
\end{figure}

\subsection{GCS Planning and Region Generation}

GCS~\cite{marcucci2024motion} casts motion planning as mixed-integer convex
programming over a graph of convex sets, admitting tight convex relaxations
that yield globally optimal trajectories.
IRIS~\cite{deits2015computing} alternates between inscribed ellipsoids and
separating hyperplanes in workspace but does not directly produce C-space regions.
IRIS-NP~\cite{petersen2023growing} grows C-space polytopes via NLP
seed-growing, achieving high volume but without a formal collision-safety certificate.
IRIS-ZO~\cite{zhong2024iris} applies zeroth-order optimization to reduce FK
evaluations, yet remains non-certified.
C-IRIS~\cite{werner2024certified} provides SOS polynomial certificates but
requires minutes per region.
FastIRIS~\cite{cohn2024fastIRIS} accelerates the IRIS iteration but does
not change the non-certified nature.
None of these methods support persistence or cross-scene reuse.

\subsection{C-space Decomposition and Cell Methods}

Exact cell decomposition~\cite{schwartz1983piano} is theoretically complete
but intractable in high dimensions.
Approximate cell decomposition~\cite{zhu1991new} employs octree/KD-tree
recursive splitting but lacks safety certification.
Approximate convex decomposition~\cite{lien2008approximate} primarily targets
workspace geometry and has not been extended to C-space certification.
SBF fills the gap ``approximate decomposition + certified safety'' by
providing interval-FK certificates for each cell.

\subsection{Interval Arithmetic in Robotics}

Interval analysis provides rigorous enclosures of function
ranges~\cite{moore2009introduction,jaulin2001applied}.
Interval FK has been used for workspace reachability
analysis~\cite{merlet2004solving} and parallel mechanism
calibration~\cite{daney2006interval}.
To the best of our knowledge, this is the first use of interval FK for
C-space region certification in the context of GCS planning.

\subsection{Multi-Query and Persistent Planning}

PRM~\cite{kavraki1996probabilistic} builds a persistent roadmap that
supports multi-query planning but provides neither convex regions nor
collision-safety certificates.
RRT and its variants~\cite{lavalle1998rapidly,kuffner2000rrt} are
widely used single-query planners but do not produce reusable convex regions.
Experience Graphs~\cite{phillips2012experience} reuse historical paths but
do not generate free-space regions.
SBF uniquely combines certified convex region generation, persistence, and
incremental updates in a single framework.

% ==============================================================================
% III. C-SPACE BOX CERTIFICATION
% ==============================================================================
\section{C-space Box Certification: Interval FK vs.\ Critical Sampling}
\label{sec:certification}

This section introduces the unified ``C-space box $\to$ workspace link-AABB
vector'' framework and develops two complementary envelope strategies that
span the safety--tightness tradeoff.

% ──── III-A. Problem Formulation ─────────────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{Problem Formulation}\label{sec:formulation}

\emph{Notation.}
Let $D$ denote the number of degrees of freedom~(DOF) and $L$ the number of collision-relevant links.
Configurations are denoted by bold lowercase letters ($\bm{q} \in \Real^D$).
A closed real interval is denoted by $[x] = [\underline{x}, \overline{x}]$, and the interval extension of a function $f$ is written as $f([x])$.
The workspace geometry of link $\ell$ at configuration $\bm{q}$ is denoted by $\mathrm{geom}_\ell(\FK(\bm{q})) \subset \Real^3$.

\emph{Input.}
A $D$-DOF serial manipulator with Denavit-Hartenberg~(DH) parameters,
a C-space hyperrectangle $B = \prod_{i=1}^{D}[\underline{q}_i,\overline{q}_i] \subset \Real^D$,
and a set of obstacle AABBs $\calO = \{O_1, \ldots, O_M\}$ in the workspace.

\emph{Goal.}
Determine whether $B \subseteq \Cfree$, \ie, the robot is collision-free
for every configuration $\bm{q} \in B$.

\begin{definition}[Link-AABB Envelope]\label{def:envelope}
For link~$\ell \in \{1,\ldots,L\}$ and C-space box~$B$, a
\emph{link-AABB envelope} is an axis-aligned bounding box satisfying
\begin{equation}\label{eq:envelope}
  \AABB_\ell(B) \supseteq \bigcup_{\bm{q} \in B}
    \mathrm{geom}_\ell\bigl(\FK(\bm{q})\bigr).
\end{equation}
The \emph{envelope vector} of $B$ is
$\calA(B) = \bigl(\AABB_1(B),\ldots,\AABB_L(B)\bigr)$.
\end{definition}

\emph{Link geometry simplification via AABB inflation.}
To streamline the computation of $\mathrm{geom}_\ell(\FK(\bm{q}))$, each robot link is modeled as a line segment connecting its two adjacent joint origins.
The AABB of the entire link over $B$ is then efficiently obtained by computing the coordinate extrema of these two endpoints and subsequently inflating the resulting bounding box by the link's collision radius.
This geometric abstraction allows the envelope to be derived solely from the endpoints' kinematics, significantly reducing computational complexity for both IFK and critical-point sampling.

We make the following standing assumption throughout the paper:
\begin{quote}
\textbf{Assumption~1} (Link geometry containment).
\emph{For each link~$\ell$, the true workspace geometry
$\mathrm{geom}_\ell(\FK(\bm{q}))$ is contained within the AABB of
the corresponding line-segment model inflated by collision
radius~$r_\ell$, for all $\bm{q} \in \Cspace$.}
\end{quote}
This is satisfied by construction when collision radii are chosen conservatively to enclose mesh geometry.

\begin{proposition}[Certification Criterion]\label{prop:cert}
If\/ $\AABB_\ell(B) \cap O_j = \emptyset$ for all links~$\ell$ and all
obstacles~$O_j$, then $B \subseteq \Cfree$.
This is a conservative sufficient condition:
a negative outcome~(intersection) does \emph{not} imply collision,
only that the box cannot be certified at this granularity.
\end{proposition}

% ──── III-B. Interval Forward Kinematics ─────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{Interval Forward Kinematics (IFK)}\label{sec:ifk}

\emph{Interval trigonometric functions.}
For a joint angle interval $[\theta] = [\underline{\theta}, \overline{\theta}]$, the exact image intervals of sine and cosine are computed via case analysis on monotonic sub-intervals and critical-point inclusion:
\begin{equation}
  \sin([\theta]) = [\underline{s},\overline{s}],
  \quad
  \cos([\theta]) = [\underline{c},\overline{c}].
\end{equation}

\emph{Interval homogeneous transforms.}
The standard DH transformation matrix $\bT_i(\theta_i)$ from frame $i$ to $i-1$ depends on constant parameters $(a_i,\alpha_i,d_i)$ and the joint variable $\theta_i \in [\theta_i]$.
Substituting the interval trigonometric functions yields an interval matrix $[\bT_i]$, where each entry is a real interval bounding the possible values of that matrix element.

\emph{Interval chain multiplication.}
The forward kinematics to frame $k$ is obtained by sequential interval matrix multiplication:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:chain}
  [\bT^{0:k}] = [\bT^{0:k-1}] \otimes [\bT_k],
\end{equation}
where $\otimes$ denotes matrix multiplication using interval arithmetic (Minkowski sum and interval product).
The AABB for link~$\ell$ is directly extracted from the translation vectors of $[\bT^{0:\ell-1}]$ and $[\bT^{0:\ell}]$ (representing the two endpoints), followed by the radius inflation.

\begin{theorem}[Certified Conservatism]\label{thm:cert}
Let $\AABB_\ell^{\mathrm{IFK}}(B)$ be the AABB computed by
interval FK for link~$\ell$ over box~$B$.  Then
$\forall \bm{q} \in B\colon
  \mathrm{geom}_\ell\bigl(\FK(\bm{q})\bigr)
  \subseteq \AABB_\ell^{\mathrm{IFK}}(B)$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Each DH transform $\bT_i(\theta_i)$ is a composition of continuous arithmetic operations applied to $\theta_i \in [\theta_i]$.
By the Fundamental Theorem of Interval Arithmetic~\cite{moore2009introduction}, the interval extension of a continuous function encloses its true range.
Since $\sin([\theta])$ and $\cos([\theta])$ yield exact range enclosures, each $[\bT_i]$ is an inclusion-monotone interval extension.
Because interval matrix multiplication~\eqref{eq:chain} preserves the inclusion property at every step, the resulting interval matrix $[\bT^{0:\ell}]$ rigorously encloses all point-valued transformations $\bT^{0:\ell}(\bm{q})$ for $\bm{q} \in B$.
Note that chain multiplication may introduce over-approximation due to the dependency problem (the \emph{wrapping effect}); this affects the \emph{tightness} of the enclosure but not its \emph{soundness}---the true range is always contained within the interval result.
Combined with Assumption~1, the derived AABB encloses the workspace geometry of link $\ell$.
\end{proof}

\emph{Complexity.}
Certifying a single box costs $O(D \cdot L_\text{active})$, where
$L_\text{active}$ is the number of links requiring collision checks.

% ──── III-C. Critical-Point Sampling ─────────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{Critical-Point Sampling (Tight, Non-Certified)}\label{sec:critical}

Interval chain multiplication introduces the \emph{wrapping
effect}~(dependency problem), yielding overly conservative AABBs.
Critical-point sampling approaches the problem from the opposite direction:
rather than bounding from above, it directly seeks the extrema of each
link's position function over~$B$ to obtain near-ground-truth tight AABBs.

\emph{Three-stage pipeline:}
\begin{enumerate}
\item \emph{Critical-point enumeration.}
  For link~$\ell$, position component $f_d(\bm{q})=p_\ell^d(\bm{q})$ attains its
  extrema on the boundary or at saddle points of~$B$.
  We enumerate the $2^{|\calR_\ell|}$ boundary vertex combinations of the
  relevant joint subset $\calR_\ell = \{1,\ldots,\ell\}$ (the joints that
  kinematically affect link~$\ell$) and evaluate $f_d$ directly.
  For a 7-DOF manipulator, $|\calR_\ell| \leq 7$, yielding at most $128$
  vertices---a modest cost.

\item \emph{Constraint-manifold sampling.}
  Random samples on the joint-coupling constraint manifold supplement
  enumeration to capture interior extrema.

\item \emph{L-BFGS-B local refinement.}
  Starting from enumeration/sampling results, a local optimizer tightens
  the bound.
\end{enumerate}

Critical sampling \emph{does not provide certified conservatism}: the
finite sample set may miss the global extremum, so
$\AABB_\ell^\text{crit}(B)$ may underestimate the true envelope.
Adding a safety margin $\epsilon>0$ compensates for potential
underestimation of the envelope:
$\AABB_\ell^{\text{crit}+\epsilon}(B)
  \;{:=}\; \AABB_\ell^\text{crit}(B) \oplus [-\epsilon,\epsilon]^3$,
but does not provide a formal certificate.

\emph{Cost.}
The per-box cost is millisecond-level (including optimization), roughly
$100$--$1000\times$ that of IFK, yet still far below C-IRIS's SOS solver.

% ──── III-D. Subdivision Enhancements ────────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{Link Subdivision and C-space Box Subdivision}\label{sec:subdivision}

Both subdivision techniques below are orthogonally applicable to IFK and
critical sampling; they trade additional computation time for tighter
envelopes.

\emph{Link subdivision.}
A long link's AABB can be excessively large.
Splitting link~$\ell$ into $n$ equal segments along its local frame and
computing AABBs independently tightens the envelope.
Under IFK, all segments share the prefix chain $\bT^{1:\ell-1}$, incurring
minimal incremental cost while \emph{preserving certification};
under critical sampling, segments share joint samples and optimization,
likewise with negligible overhead.

\emph{C-space box subdivision.}
Bisecting $B$ along a dimension into $B_1,B_2$ and computing AABBs
separately yields tighter enclosures.
Recursive $k$-level subdivision produces $2^k$ sub-boxes.
Under IFK, sub-boxes share prefix transforms and \emph{certification is
preserved}
($\bigcup_i \AABB_\ell(B_i) \subseteq \AABB_\ell(B)$ but tighter);
under critical sampling, smaller search domains improve extremum enumeration
accuracy.

Both subdivision techniques compose orthogonally with each other and with
the envelope strategy.
Thanks to computation sharing (prefix chain reuse for IFK, sample reuse for
critical), time overhead grows sub-linearly while tightness improves
significantly---empirically $2$--$5\times$ for IFK and beyond $10\times$
for critical with combined subdivisions.

% ──── III-E. Safety–Tightness Tradeoff ───────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{Safety--Tightness Tradeoff}\label{sec:tradeoff}

\Cref{tab:tradeoff} summarizes the two envelope strategies.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Safety--tightness tradeoff of envelope strategies.}
\label{tab:tradeoff}
\footnotesize
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcccc@{}}
\toprule
Strategy & Cert. & Rel.\ Tight. & Cost / box & Use case \\
\midrule
IFK         & \checkmark & $1.0\times$ & $O(DL)$, $\mu$s & Safety-critical \\
IFK + subdiv. & \checkmark & $2$--$5\times$ & $\mu$s (sub-lin.) & Safety + coverage \\
Critical    & $\times$   & $5$--$10\times$ & ms & Offline planning \\
Crit.\ + subdiv. & $\times$ & $>10\times$ & ms (sub-lin.) & Max coverage \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{remark}[Random-sampling baseline]
Uniform random sampling of $N$ configurations plus L-BFGS-B refinement
yields $3$--$7\times$ tightness without certification and at the highest
cost.
It serves only as an experimental baseline.
\end{remark}

The strategy choice (IFK vs.\ critical) determines the safety level;
subdivision parameters $(n,k)$ adjust the time--tightness curve within a
given strategy.
The two dimensions are orthogonal: users select according to application
requirements (safety-critical vs.\ offline high-coverage) and time budget.
The SBF framework is transparent to both choices---the forest layer
(\cref{sec:sbf}) requires no modification.

% ==============================================================================
% IV. SAFEBOXFOREST
% ==============================================================================
\section{SafeBoxForest: Construction, Persistence, and GCS Integration}
\label{sec:sbf}

% ──── IV-A. HierAABBTree ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{Hierarchical C-space Cache (HierAABBTree)}
\label{sec:sbf_construction}

\emph{Data structure.}
A KD-tree--style hierarchical binary partition tree in which each node~$v$
stores a C-space box $B_v$:
the root covers $\Cspace$;
child nodes bisect a parent along one dimension;
each node caches its link-AABB vector
$\calA(B_v) = \{\AABB_1(B_v),\ldots,\AABB_L(B_v)\}$.

\emph{Incremental FK prefix reuse.}
When node~$v$ splits along dimension~$d$ into $v_L,v_R$, the interval
transform chain $[\bT^{0:d-1}]$ for joints $1,\ldots,d{-}1$ is unchanged;
only $[\bT^{d:D}]$ needs recomputation.
This saves $\approx 43\%$ of computation on average (measured on IIWA14
7-DOF).

\emph{Find Free Box (FFB).}
Given a seed configuration $\bm{q}_\text{seed}$, FFB performs a top-down search from the root:
\begin{enumerate}
\item If node $B_v$ is collision-free $\to$ \emph{promotion}: return $B_v$
  (largest collision-free ancestor).
\item If collision $\to$ \emph{split}: bisect along the widest dimension,
  recurse into the child containing $\bm{q}_\text{seed}$.
\item At minimum-granularity leaf $\to$ return $\emptyset$ (mark as occupied).
\end{enumerate}

\emph{Active split dimensions.}
Dimensions that do not affect any collision-relevant link geometry
are automatically excluded, reducing unnecessary splits.
For instance, if the last joint induces only a rotation about the link's
symmetry axis so that the link AABB remains invariant, that dimension
can be skipped.

% ──── IV-B. Forest Construction ──────────────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{Forest Construction Algorithm}\label{sec:sbf_forest}

\begin{definition}[SafeBoxForest]
A non-overlapping certified box set
$\calF = \{B_1,\ldots,B_N\}$ with adjacency graph $G=(V,E)$ satisfying:
\begin{itemize}
\item[\textbf{I1}] \emph{Non-overlapping}:
  $\mathrm{int}(B_i) \cap \mathrm{int}(B_j) = \emptyset,\;\forall i \neq j$.
\item[\textbf{I2}] \emph{Face-adjacency}:
  $(B_i,B_j)\in E \Leftrightarrow B_i,B_j$ share a $(D{-}1)$-dimensional face.
\item[\textbf{I3}] \emph{Endpoint coverage}:
  $\bm{q}_\text{start} \in \bigcup_i B_i$ and
  $\bm{q}_\text{goal} \in \bigcup_i B_i$.
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

The construction procedure is given in \cref{alg:sbf}.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{SafeBoxForest Construction}\label{alg:sbf}
\footnotesize
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\REQUIRE Robot~$R$, obstacles~$\calO$, $\bm{q}_\text{start}$, $\bm{q}_\text{goal}$,
  max boxes $N_{\max}$, random seeds $N_{\text{rand}}$
\ENSURE SafeBoxForest~$\calF$, GCS graph~$G$
\STATE Initialize HierAABBTree~$T$ (load HCACHE if available)
\STATE $B_s \leftarrow \text{FFB}(T, \bm{q}_\text{start}, \calO)$;\;
       $B_g \leftarrow \text{FFB}(T, \bm{q}_\text{goal}, \calO)$
\STATE $Q \leftarrow \{B_s, B_g\}$;\;
       $\calF \leftarrow \{B_s, B_g\}$
\WHILE{$|\calF| < N_{\max}$ \AND $Q \neq \emptyset$}
  \STATE $B \leftarrow \text{dequeue}(Q)$
  \FORALL{face $f \in \partial B$}
    \STATE $\bm{q}_\text{seed} \leftarrow \text{sample\_outside\_face}(f, \epsilon)$
    \IF{goal\_bias()}
      \STATE $\bm{q}_\text{seed} \leftarrow \text{perturb\_toward}(\bm{q}_\text{seed}, \bm{q}_\text{goal})$
    \ENDIF
    \STATE $B_\text{new} \leftarrow \text{FFB}(T, \bm{q}_\text{seed}, \calO)$
    \IF{$B_\text{new} \neq \emptyset$ \AND $B_\text{new} \notin \calF$}
      \STATE $\calF \leftarrow \calF \cup \{B_\text{new}\}$;\;
             $Q \leftarrow Q \cup \{B_\text{new}\}$
    \ENDIF
  \ENDFOR
\ENDWHILE
\STATE \COMMENT{Free Interval Weighted Sampling}
\FOR{$i=1$ \TO $N_{\text{rand}}$}
  \STATE $\bm{q}_\text{seed} \leftarrow \text{sample\_free\_interval\_weighted}(\calF)$
  \STATE $B_\text{new} \leftarrow \text{FFB}(T, \bm{q}_\text{seed}, \calO)$
  \IF{$B_\text{new} \neq \emptyset$}
    \STATE $\calF \leftarrow \calF \cup \{B_\text{new}\}$
  \ENDIF
\ENDFOR
\STATE \COMMENT{Bridge Paving}
\STATE $\mathcal{C} \leftarrow \text{connected\_components}(\calF)$
\FORALL{pair $(C_i,C_j) \in \mathcal{C} \times \mathcal{C}$}
  \STATE $\text{bridge\_paving}(T, C_i, C_j, \calO, \calF)$
\ENDFOR
\STATE $\calF \leftarrow \text{coarsen}(\calF)$ \COMMENT{merge aligned boxes}
\STATE $G \leftarrow \text{build\_adjacency}(\calF)$
\STATE $\text{save\_hcache}(T)$
\RETURN $\calF, G$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\emph{Seed strategies.}
\emph{BFS wavefront} (lines~4--14): starting from $B_s$ and $B_g$, boxes
expand outward via $\epsilon$-offset face sampling with goal bias.
\emph{Free-interval weighting} (lines~16--19): sampling weighted by
per-dimension uncovered interval length fills coverage gaps.
\emph{Bridge paving} (lines~21--23): isolated connected components are
bridged in three steps---a \emph{dry-run FFB} probes whether a candidate
seed between two components can yield a free box; an \emph{overlap check}
ensures the new box does not violate I1; a \emph{formal FFB} then
inserts the box into $\calF$.
If direct bridging fails, an internal RRT-Connect~\cite{kuffner2000rrt}
finds a collision-free path between the components, along which additional
boxes are paved to restore connectivity.

% ──── IV-C. HCACHE Persistence ───────────────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{HCACHE Persistence}\label{sec:hcache}

Link AABBs depend \emph{only} on robot kinematics and are
\emph{obstacle-independent}---the same robot can reuse them across scenes.
The HCACHE binary format persists the entire HierAABBTree:
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Lazy load}: nodes are read from disk (or computed) only when
  touched by FFB queries.
\item \emph{Incremental write}: only dirty/new nodes are serialized via
  mmap append.
\item \emph{Cross-scene reuse}: upon scene change, HCACHE is not rebuilt;
  collision detection simply compares cached AABBs against new obstacles.
\end{itemize}
After warm start, the FK phase takes $<\!1$\,ms, shifting the bottleneck
entirely to collision detection.

% ──── IV-D. Incremental Update ───────────────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{Incremental Update}\label{sec:incremental}

When the obstacle set changes from $\calO$ to $\calO'$, IRIS-family methods
cannot pinpoint invalidated regions and must fully reconstruct at cost
$O(N \cdot T_\text{IRIS})$.
SBF performs a three-step incremental update:
\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Invalidate}: for each $B_i \in \calF$, check whether
  $\calA(B_i)$ collides with new/moved obstacles; mark the invalidated set
  $\calF_\text{inv}$.
\item \textbf{Remove}: delete $\calF_\text{inv}$ from $\calF$ and $G$.
\item \textbf{Regrow}: use the centers of invalidated boxes as seeds and
  call FFB to refill.
\end{enumerate}
Complexity: $O(|\calF_\text{inv}| \cdot H \cdot D \cdot L)$,
where $H$ is the tree height.
For uniform bisection with minimum edge length $\delta_{\min}$,
$H = O(D \cdot \log_2(\pi / \delta_{\min}))$;
e.g., with $\delta_{\min} = 0.01$\,rad the tree height is $\approx 63$
for a 7-DOF arm.

% ──── IV-E. GCS Graph Generation ─────────────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{GCS Graph Generation}\label{sec:gcs}

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Coarsen}: dimension-scan merge of aligned adjacent boxes to
  reduce GCS node count.
\item \textbf{Node mapping}: each $B_i$ maps to a GCS HPolyhedron node
  (hyperrectangles are naturally HPolyhedra).
\item \textbf{Edge construction}: face-adjacent box pairs form edges;
  continuity constraints hold naturally on shared faces.
\item \textbf{Endpoint insertion}: the boxes containing $\bm{q}_\text{start}$
  and $\bm{q}_\text{goal}$ serve as source and target.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{remark}[Resolution Completeness]
If $\Cfree$ contains a path whose $\ell_\infty$-clearance is
$\geq \delta$ and the HierAABBTree minimum leaf edge length
$\delta_{\min} \leq \delta/2$, then FFB can certify a chain of
boxes covering the path.
SBF therefore possesses \emph{resolution completeness}; the parameter
$\delta_{\min}$ serves as the resolution control.
\end{remark}

