% ==============================================================================
% VI. CONCLUSION
% ==============================================================================
\section{Conclusion}\label{sec:conclusion}

We presented SafeBoxForest, a persistent C-space decomposition
framework with interval-FK certification, providing certified convex
regions for GCS motion planning.
Its obstacle-independent kinematic cache~(HCACHE) and incremental update
mechanism transform region generation from ``rebuild every time'' to
``incremental maintenance,'' reducing amortized multi-query cost.
Comprehensive experiments on a KUKA IIWA14 7-DOF manipulator across three
obstacle-density scenes validate SBF's advantages in safety certification,
generation efficiency, and free-space coverage.

\textbf{Limitations.}
Hyperrectangles are geometrically simple: individual box volume is smaller
than that of polytopes, requiring more boxes to achieve comparable coverage
in dense narrow passages (though aggregate coverage remains competitive).
The current formulation applies only to serial manipulators with DH
kinematics.
Additionally, obstacles must be represented as AABBs; curved or concave
obstacles need conservative AABB over-approximation.
In high-DOF settings, the wrapping effect of interval chain multiplication
may cause excessive false rejections, limiting the proportion of C-space
that can be certified at coarse granularity.

\textbf{Future work.}
Future directions include exploring Oriented Bounding Box~(OBB) envelopes
for tighter geometric bounds, which could substantially reduce the
wrapping-induced conservatism.
Parallelizing the BFS wavefront and collision detection across multiple
cores could further accelerate region generation.
Finally, optimizing envelope unions through more refined geometric merge
strategies may improve aggregate coverage without sacrificing certification.

